Treading with Tunes

A study conducted on the effects of music on oneâ€™s walking speed

participants

Although we are physically very different, we are both music lovers and frequent walkers!

data collection

Data was collected using the iOS Health app for walking speed and stride information, and the Last.fm app for music listening history. We collected data over the course of 2 months.

Lets get some terminology out of the way!

genre

Genre refers to the main category of music. While numerous musical pieces may belong to multiple genres or even have various sub-genres, they typically possess a primary genre that defines their overarching style.

EX: As It Was by Harry Styles - Pop

BPM

BPM, also known as beats per minute, is a measure of how fast the musicâ€™s tempo is. The larger the number, song usually have a faster tempo. However, some slow songs have a very fast BPM, this is because when the BPM is too fast, you can sync to half of the BPM.

EX: Don't Stop Me Now by Queen - 80

EX: Cementerio Club by Pescado Rabioso - 40

walking speed

Walking speed is determined by the time it takes to cover a specific distance by walking (mph).

The dependent variable in our study is walking speed. We want to find out what factor changes this variable the most!

EX: Mikeâ€™s avg daily walking speed is 3.6 mph

stride

Stride refers to the distance between successive steps when walking.

The chart to the right shows the difference between our strides, helping to show that our data has been collected by two very different walkers.

EX: 31.1in

genre + bpm mix

Now that we take a look at BPM distribution per genre, it doesnâ€™t seem like the genre of a song affects its tempo very much.

beat-p-m

Each dot on this chart is a song that we listened to while walking. The songs are color coded by genre.

After collecting data for a couple weeks, we noticed a very evident correlation between walking speed and BPM. The faster the BPM of music we listened to, the quicker we walked.

play-testing

Based off of what we learned from tracking our walking speed with different music, we curated two different playlists with the songs that exhibited the fastest, and slowest walking speeds.

We then listened to these playlists over the next couple weeks to test if theyâ€™re the real deal.

taking control!

After listening to our newly created playlists for 2 weeks, there is a noticeable increase that can be seen in the correlation between BPM and walk speed. This means that the playlists that we created were successful in unconsciously manipulating our walking speed through extra fast, or extra slow BPMs.
